{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1770129142,"nonce":"M5ss/LwihQQIDOAxpNFL+0H8GxU=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87n9LNP","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/139","origin":"github"},"title":"Adopt Conductor-Inspired Workflow Patterns (Framework-Agnostic)","message":"## Summary\n\nImprove workspace planning and workflow discipline by adopting beneficial patterns from the Conductor plugin, while maintaining multi-agent compatibility.\n\n## Motivation\n\nAfter evaluating Conductor (see #136), we identified valuable workflow patterns that align with our \"context as code\" philosophy. While Conductor itself is incompatible (Gemini CLI-only), we can implement similar patterns in a framework-agnostic way.\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nCurrent workflow lacks:\n1. **Structured planning** - Issues vary in detail/format\n2. **Plan-before-code enforcement** - Agents sometimes jump to implementation\n3. **Phase verification** - No systematic checkpoints during multi-phase work\n4. **Feature-level git operations** - Reverting features requires manual commit hunting\n\n## Proposed Solution\n\nImplement four Conductor-inspired patterns using our existing `.agent/` infrastructure:\n\n### 1. Structured Track Planning (GitHub Issue Template)\n\n**Create**: `.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature_track.md`\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: Feature Track\nabout: Structured planning for features and bugs\n---\n\n## Spec\n\n**User Story**: \n[As a {user}, I want {goal}, so that {benefit}]\n\n**Acceptance Criteria**:\n- [ ] Criterion 1\n- [ ] Criterion 2\n\n**Out of Scope**:\n- Item 1\n- Item 2\n\n## Plan\n\n### Phase 1: {Name}\n- [ ] Task 1\n  - [ ] Subtask 1a\n  - [ ] Subtask 1b\n- [ ] Task 2\n\n### Phase 2: {Name}\n- [ ] Task 3\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n[Agent fills this section during work with key decisions, challenges, etc.]\n\n## Verification\n\n- [ ] Tests pass\n- [ ] Documentation updated\n- [ ] User verified behavior\n\n---\n**Effort Estimate**: {Small/Medium/Large}\n**Priority**: {High/Medium/Low}\n```\n\n**Benefits**:\n- Consistent issue structure\n- Forces planning before implementation\n- Clear verification criteria\n- Agent-friendly format\n\n### 2. Plan-Before-Code Rule\n\n**Update**: `.agent/AI_RULES.md`\n\nAdd section:\n```markdown\n## Rule: Plan Before Implement\n\nFor all features and non-trivial bug fixes:\n\n1. **Spec First**: Create or review specification\n   - What are we building?\n   - Why is this needed?\n   - What are acceptance criteria?\n   - What is out of scope?\n\n2. **Plan Next**: Break down into phases/tasks\n   - Create task breakdown with subtasks\n   - Identify dependencies\n   - Estimate effort for each phase\n\n3. **Get Approval**: Show plan to user\n   - Present spec and plan\n   - Wait for user confirmation\n   - Adjust based on feedback\n\n4. **Then Implement**: Only after approval\n   - Follow plan systematically\n   - Update task checkboxes as you progress\n   - Document key decisions in issue\n\n**Exception**: Trivial changes (typos, formatting, obvious fixes) can skip planning.\n\n**Enforcement**: Agents should refuse to implement features without an approved plan.\n```\n\n### 3. Phase Verification Checkpoints\n\n**Update**: `.agent/workflows/` and `AI_RULES.md`\n\nAdd checkpoint protocol:\n```markdown\n## Phase Verification Protocol\n\nAfter completing each major phase in a multi-phase feature:\n\n1. **Run Tests**: Execute relevant test suite\n   ```bash\n   colcon test --packages-select {package}\n   colcon test-result --verbose\n   ```\n\n2. **Build Verification**: Ensure clean build\n   ```bash\n   colcon build --packages-select {package}\n   ```\n\n3. **User Checkpoint**: Pause and ask user\n   - \"Phase {N} complete. Please verify:\"\n   - List what was accomplished\n   - Ask user to test/review behavior\n   - Wait for approval before continuing\n\n4. **Update Plan**: Mark phase complete in issue\n   - Check off phase tasks\n   - Document any deviations from plan\n   - Note any issues discovered\n\n**Purpose**: Catch problems early, keep user in loop, ensure alignment.\n```\n\n### 4. Git-Aware Feature Revert\n\n**Create**: `.agent/scripts/revert_feature.sh`\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n# Revert all commits associated with a GitHub issue/feature\n\nusage() {\n    echo \"Usage: revert_feature.sh --issue \u003cnumber\u003e [--dry-run]\"\n    echo \"\"\n    echo \"Reverts all commits that reference the given issue number.\"\n    echo \"\"\n    echo \"Options:\"\n    echo \"  --issue \u003cnum\u003e   GitHub issue number to revert\"\n    echo \"  --dry-run       Show what would be reverted without doing it\"\n    exit 1\n}\n\n# Parse arguments\nISSUE=\"\"\nDRY_RUN=false\n\nwhile [[ $# -gt 0 ]]; do\n    case $1 in\n        --issue)\n            ISSUE=\"$2\"\n            shift 2\n            ;;\n        --dry-run)\n            DRY_RUN=true\n            shift\n            ;;\n        *)\n            usage\n            ;;\n    esac\ndone\n\nif [ -z \"$ISSUE\" ]; then\n    usage\nfi\n\n# Find commits mentioning this issue\nCOMMITS=$(git log --all --grep=\"#$ISSUE\" --oneline --reverse)\n\nif [ -z \"$COMMITS\" ]; then\n    echo \"No commits found referencing issue #$ISSUE\"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\necho \"Commits to revert for issue #$ISSUE:\"\necho \"$COMMITS\"\necho \"\"\n\nif [ \"$DRY_RUN\" = true ]; then\n    echo \"[DRY RUN] Would revert these commits (newest to oldest)\"\n    exit 0\nfi\n\nread -p \"Revert these commits? (y/n) \" -n 1 -r\necho\nif [[ ! $REPLY =~ ^[Yy]$ ]]; then\n    echo \"Aborted.\"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\n# Revert in reverse order (newest first)\ngit log --all --grep=\"#$ISSUE\" --format=%H --reverse | tac | while read commit; do\n    echo \"Reverting $commit...\"\n    git revert --no-edit \"$commit\" || {\n        echo \"Conflict during revert. Resolve manually and run 'git revert --continue'\"\n        exit 1\n    }\ndone\n\necho \"✅ Successfully reverted all commits for issue #$ISSUE\"\n```\n\n**Usage**:\n```bash\n# Preview what would be reverted\n.agent/scripts/revert_feature.sh --issue 137 --dry-run\n\n# Actually revert\n.agent/scripts/revert_feature.sh --issue 137\n```\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: GitHub Issue Template\n- [ ] Create `.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature_track.md`\n- [ ] Test template creates properly formatted issues\n- [ ] Add link to template in CONTRIBUTING.md\n- [ ] Update existing templates if needed\n\n### Task 2: Plan-Before-Code Rule\n- [ ] Add \"Plan Before Implement\" section to `.agent/AI_RULES.md`\n- [ ] Include examples of good/bad planning\n- [ ] Add exception cases (trivial fixes)\n- [ ] Update `AI_CLI_QUICKSTART.md` to reference this rule\n\n### Task 3: Phase Verification Protocol\n- [ ] Add checkpoint protocol to `.agent/AI_RULES.md`\n- [ ] Create example workflow showing phase verification\n- [ ] Document in `CLI_COMMANDS.md`\n- [ ] Add to agent onboarding materials\n\n### Task 4: Feature Revert Script\n- [ ] Create `.agent/scripts/revert_feature.sh`\n- [ ] Make executable (`chmod +x`)\n- [ ] Test with dry-run mode\n- [ ] Test actual revert on test branch\n- [ ] Add to `CLI_COMMANDS.md` documentation\n- [ ] Add Makefile target: `make revert-feature ISSUE=\u003cnum\u003e`\n\n### Task 5: Documentation \u0026 Examples\n- [ ] Add examples to CONTRIBUTING.md\n- [ ] Create sample feature track issue\n- [ ] Document in agent instruction files\n- [ ] Add to `CHANGELOG.md`\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- ✅ New GitHub issue template available for feature tracks\n- ✅ \"Plan Before Implement\" rule added to AI_RULES.md\n- ✅ Phase verification protocol documented\n- ✅ Feature revert script works for single and multi-commit features\n- ✅ All changes documented in user-facing docs\n- ✅ Agents can discover and follow new patterns\n\n## Benefits\n\n1. **Consistency**: All features follow same planning format\n2. **Quality**: Planning phase catches issues before code is written\n3. **Communication**: User stays informed with phase checkpoints\n4. **Reversibility**: Easy to undo features that don't work out\n5. **Agent-Friendly**: Clear, enforceable rules for AI agents\n6. **Framework-Agnostic**: Works with all AI tools (Copilot, Gemini, Antigravity)\n\n## Effort Estimate\n\n**Medium** (4-6 hours)\n- Task 1: 1 hour\n- Task 2: 1 hour  \n- Task 3: 1 hour\n- Task 4: 2 hours (includes testing)\n- Task 5: 1 hour\n\n## Priority\n\n**Medium** - Process improvement, not blocking current work\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- None - can be implemented independently\n\n## Related Issues\n\n- #136 - Investigate conductor plugin (spawned this issue)\n\n---\n**🤖 Authored-By**: `Copilot CLI Agent` (Claude Sonnet 4.5)","files":null}]}